        marks: 6, tier: 'amber',
        modelAnswer: `• A floating-point number is stored as three fields: a sign bit, a signed fractional mantissa and a signed integer exponent. The represented value is mantissa × 2^exponent.\n• In two\'s-complement form, a positive normalised mantissa starts 0.1... and a negative normalised mantissa starts 1.0... (sign bit different from the first fraction bit).\n• Normalisation maximises precision because every mantissa bit after the sign bit carries useful information; unnormalised forms waste mantissa bits on leading redundant 0s/1s.\n• Worked example: 0.0011010 × 2^5 → shift left twice, decrement exponent twice: 0.0110100 × 2^4 → 0.1101000 × 2^3 (normalised — starts 0.1).\n• Trade-off: range is governed by the exponent width; widening the mantissa at the cost of exponent bits improves precision but reduces range (and vice-versa). Values that do not fit exactly cause rounding error.`
