        q: 'Compare arrays, linked lists and hash tables as general-purpose data structures. Evaluate which would be the most appropriate choice for (a) a dictionary of English words with their definitions, and (b) a sequence of readings from a temperature sensor that must be processed in chronological order.',
        marks: 10, tier: 'red',
        modelAnswer: `Arrays:\n• Fixed-size (or dynamic) contiguous block; O(1) indexed access, excellent cache locality.\n• Insertion/deletion in the middle costs O(n); growing a dynamic array occasionally triggers reallocation.\n• Best when the size is known or grows predictably and random access by index is common.\nLinked lists:\n• Nodes hold a value and pointer(s); insert/delete at a known position is O(1) once that position is reached.\n• O(n) random access because traversal is required; poor cache locality owing to scattered memory.\n• Good for queues, pointer-based stacks, or sequences that grow/shrink unpredictably at the ends.\nHash tables:\n• Key-to-index mapping via a hash function; average O(1) insert, lookup and delete.\n• Poor at ordered traversal and range queries; worst-case O(n) with bad hash or high load factor; resizing is expensive.\n• Best for key-based lookup where order is irrelevant.\n(a) English dictionary:\n• Lookups dominate: given a word, return its definition quickly.\n• A hash table keyed on the word gives near-O(1) lookup — far better than scanning an array (O(n)) or a linked list (O(n)).\n• If prefix/autocomplete support is needed, a trie or balanced BST is preferable; a plain hash table cannot efficiently list "all words starting with pre-".\n• Evaluation: hash table is best for pure lookup; a trie better supports prefix queries; a balanced BST supports ordered traversal. Real dictionary apps often combine a hash table with a trie.\n(b) Temperature readings processed in order:\n• Data arrives in time order and is consumed in the same order — a classic FIFO pattern.\n• A dynamic array used as a ring buffer, or a linked-list queue, is ideal. A ring-buffer array offers O(1) enqueue/dequeue, contiguous memory (good cache behaviour) and a bounded capacity.\n• A hash table is inappropriate because temporal order is intrinsic; random access by key is not required.\n• Evaluation: an array-backed queue is the most efficient and predictable choice; a linked-list queue is acceptable if buffer size is highly variable.\nOverall: the "best" data structure depends on the dominant operation. Hash tables excel at key lookup, arrays at indexed/bulk processing with cache locality, and linked lists at dynamic insertion at pointer-known positions. Good system design matches the structure to the access pattern.`
