        marks: 10, tier: 'red',
        modelAnswer: `Legal framework in the UK:\n• The Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 (RIPA) governs interception of communications, directed surveillance and acquisition of communications data.\n• The Investigatory Powers Act 2016 (IPA) — the "Snooper\'s Charter" — updated and extended these powers, authorising bulk interception, bulk acquisition, bulk equipment interference (hacking) and 12-month Internet Connection Records held by ISPs.\n• Under the IPA, most warrants require a "double lock": ministerial approval PLUS a Judicial Commissioner\'s approval. The Investigatory Powers Commissioner\'s Office (IPCO) oversees use; the Investigatory Powers Tribunal (IPT) hears complaints.\n• Separately the DPA 2018 / UK GDPR applies to personal data processing, and the Human Rights Act 1998 protects private life under Article 8 ECHR.\nBenefits:\n• Help detect and disrupt serious crime (terrorism, organised crime, child sexual exploitation) using bulk metadata analysis.\n• Support investigations where targeted methods are insufficient (e.g. identifying previously unknown associates).\n• ICRs can place a suspect\'s device at a service relevant to an offence.\nRisks:\n• Erosion of the right to privacy and a chilling effect on protest, journalism and whistleblowing.\n• Function creep — data collected for terrorism used for immigration enforcement, minor offences.\n• Disproportionate impact on minorities and activist groups if targeting criteria embed existing biases.\n• Very large aggregated datasets become attractive targets for criminals or hostile states; one breach can be catastrophic.\n• Pressure for encryption backdoors weakens security for all users — encryption cannot be "selectively" broken.\nReal case — Snowden 2013:\n• The Snowden disclosures revealed programmes such as PRISM and Tempora and prompted global litigation. UK courts and the ECHR have since found aspects of pre-IPA bulk surveillance incompatible with Article 8. The IPA 2016 codified safeguards (double lock, IPCO) partly in response.\nEvaluation:\n• An absolutist "surveillance always justified if it saves lives" position ignores proportionality and chilling effects and cannot be defended.\n• A blanket "all surveillance is wrong" position ignores real threats that targeted, judicially authorised surveillance can address.\n• A defensible position: surveillance may be justified where (i) proportionate to the threat, (ii) targeted methods are considered first, (iii) there is strong independent judicial oversight, (iv) retention and access limits are strict, and (v) data subjects have effective remedies.\n• The UK framework is a workable but imperfect compromise — bulk powers in particular remain contested. Democratic review must keep pace with technology; otherwise public trust (without which intelligence work is harder) erodes.`
