        modelAnswer: `Automation of the workforce:\n• Industrial, retail and now cognitive automation (generative AI) are displacing work at an accelerating pace.\n• Benefits: higher productivity, cheaper goods, removing dull/dirty/dangerous work, 24/7 operation, new roles (AI engineers, data curators).\n• Harms: short-term job displacement concentrated in specific sectors and regions; widening inequality; loss of tacit skills; social effects (dignity, community, purpose). Capital owners benefit most; retraining costs often fall on the taxpayer.\nE-waste and minerals:\n• The UN reported 62 million tonnes of e-waste in 2022, growing five times faster than recycling. Informal yards (e.g. Agbogbloshie, Ghana) expose workers to dioxins and poison groundwater.\n• Cobalt for lithium-ion batteries (~70% from the DRC) involves documented child and artisanal labour; lithium extraction depletes groundwater in the Atacama; rare-earth processing is geopolitically concentrated.\n• The UK WEEE Regulations 2013 require producer-funded collection; the EU Right to Repair Directive 2024 forces spare-part availability.\nData-centre energy:\n• Data centres consumed ~1–1.5% of global electricity pre-AI boom and are rising with LLM training and crypto-mining. Bitcoin alone uses more electricity than some countries.\n• Mitigations: 24/7 clean-energy matching (Google), liquid cooling, workload scheduling following renewable generation; Ethereum\'s 2022 move to proof-of-stake cut its energy use ~99.95%.\n• Positives: smart grids, precision agriculture, climate modelling, reduced paper use — computing also reduces environmental harm when deployed deliberately.\nDigital divide:\n• Access, skills and outcomes gaps (urban/rural, economic, generational, disability, linguistic). COVID-19 schooling exposed the divide; policy responses include Project Gigabit, WCAG 2.1 AA, the Equality Act.\nResponsibilities:\n• Governments — strong data-protection and competition law (Digital Markets, Competition and Consumers Act 2024), WEEE/Right to Repair, rural broadband investment, accessibility duties, fair taxation across jurisdictions, support retraining schemes.\n• Companies — comply with the spirit of regulation, publish environmental and workforce data, invest in clean-energy and repairable design, audit AI for bias, support content moderators, respect international supply-chain standards.\n• Individuals — make informed choices (repairable devices, privacy-preserving tools, exercising DPA rights, recycling responsibly), hold companies to account via consumer and democratic pressure, avoid "tech fatalism".\nEvaluation:\n• No single actor solves these issues. Regulation is the floor but is evadable by offshoring; companies profit-maximise within the rules; individuals lack leverage alone.\n• A layered approach — internationally coordinated regulation, transparent corporate reporting, professional codes (BCS, ACM) and informed, active users — is the most defensible path. Ethical technology at global scale requires collective action rather than purely individual responsibility.`
