        modelAnswer: `Role of Big-O in practice:\n• Big-O describes how running time (or memory) scales with input size, ignoring hardware-specific constants. It is the right tool to answer "does this still work when n gets 10× or 100× larger?".\n• It provides a principled way to rule out algorithms that clearly will not scale (e.g. O(n²) where O(n log n) is available for large n), before any code is written or benchmarked.\n• It also guides data-structure choice (e.g. hash table O(1) vs balanced BST O(log n)).\nLimitations of Big-O:\n• Big-O hides constant factors, lower-order terms, and sometimes memory-hierarchy effects. Two algorithms both labelled O(n log n) can differ by 10× in practice.\n• Worst-case Big-O may not reflect typical behaviour: quicksort is average-O(n log n) but worst-O(n²); hash tables are average-O(1) but worst-O(n). The shape of real-world input matters.\n• Big-O does not distinguish cache-friendly sequential access from cache-hostile random access, though that dominates modern CPU performance.\n• Parallelism, I/O cost and network latency are outside the model — they can swamp the algorithmic cost for real systems.\nExample where better Big-O is not the right choice:\n• Sorting a list of 10 items: insertion sort (O(n²)) is almost always faster in practice than merge sort (O(n log n)) because it has much smaller constants and zero allocation, even though merge sort has better asymptotic complexity. Hybrid sorts (e.g. Timsort, introsort) exploit this by falling back to insertion sort on small sub-arrays.\n• Another example: a linear scan on an array may outperform a balanced BST lookup for a few hundred items, because of cache locality and branch prediction, despite O(n) vs. O(log n) on paper.\nConclusion:\n• Big-O is an indispensable starting point for algorithm selection but is not a substitute for understanding the input distribution, hardware, and measuring on representative data. In practice, strong systems combine the best Big-O feasible with careful attention to constants and memory behaviour.`
